Under a Threat of Extinction: Three cheetah cubs were born in Iran
The world's fastest animal is falling prey to ruthless hunting, traps, and deadly road accidents throughout the Islamic Republic.
As a result, the population of the cheetahs has dropped to less than 20.
Three Asiatic cheetah cubs recently appeared into the world in the Islamic Republic of Iran.
This is a rare birth, offering only a slight improvement to the tragic situation of the endangered animal in the country due to droughts, hunting, and fatal road accidents.
This marks the first captive-born cheetah birth in Iran.
It's worth noting that the Islamic Republic is one of the last countries in the world where cheetahs still exist in the wild.
Iran's news agency 'IRNA' reported that the veterinary team, trusted by the Toran National Park in the northern Semnan province, has opted for a captive cesarean birth.
Furthermore, it was noted that fewer than 20 cheetahs have been documented in seven different provinces across the country in recent times.
In response to the threat of their extinction, the United Nations implemented a protection program for them as early as 2001.
Now, in Iran, there is hope that these new cubs could potentially contribute to the growth of the cheetah population in the future.
Last January, Iran's Deputy Minister of Environment, Hassan Akhbari, revealed that the cheetah population in the country has dramatically declined. In 2010, there were around 100 falcons, whereas now there are only 12 left.
“Their situation is extremely dire," stated Akhbari, emphasizing that the cheetahs have fallen victim to drought in their native habitats, as well as to road accidents.
The cheetah is considered the fastest creature in the world, capable of reaching speeds of approximately 100 kilometers per hour.
Cheetahs can be found in various locations across the globe, spanning from India to Senegal in West Africa.
Spotify wants to upgrade your vehicle: We've reviewed the Car Thing
Quietly, Spotify has begun to try its luck in the hardware world as well
After years of development, Car Thing has been unveiled and launched as a small-scale trial in the United States
We've got our hands on the first device in Israel
The Vision: Transforming Your Old Cars into Smart Vehicles
Car Thing is Spotify's first hardware product, uniquely designed to offer a solution for owners of older vehicles.
A few weeks ago, I had the initial opportunity to try out the new product, which is currently available only to select testers in the US, here in Israel.
For me, the timing of the delivery was quite uncanny, as our family car broke down, and we had to drive a loaned vehicle with an outdated system for a few days.
After two weeks of enjoyment, I realized how the Car Thing can seamlessly become an integral part of many people's systems.
On the other hand, with a long waiting list and uncertainty regarding global launch, I believe many will opt for alternative solutions.
From Concept to Reality
Somewhere in 2018, Spotify users began receiving an intriguing offer in their email inbox - a chance to purchase a new device with voice control and fourth-generation connectivity, transforming any older system into a smart car.
The rumors gradually faded until a year later when the Financial Times revealed that the company was soon to unveil a new product for cars, simulating a smart radio with Bluetooth connectivity.
A few months later, these rumors resurfaced after the music service updated with a car mode - the same one we recognize today from the app -activated once the smartphone detects a connection to the vehicle system.
Two years have passed since then.
After countless rumors and leaks, Spotify finally unveiled 'Car Thing' in April, its smart in-car system.
Spotify opted to release the new device in an extremely limited manner, with a long waiting list and significant delays in terms of shipments.
So, naturally, right after the press conference, I went to the website and signed up.
Two months later, the anticipated message arrived.
A renewed website login will grant me the opportunity to purchase the device with a small surprise - it won't cost me a thing.
After another month of waiting, the courier finally knocked on my door, accompanied by a small box adorned with the Spotify logo.
The Car Thing.
First and foremost, Spotify's device impressed me greatly with its build quality.
It's slightly smaller than my iPhone 11 and features a large, bright, and crisp touchscreen on its front.
Additionally, right next to the screen, you'll find a circular knob that you can rotate to navigate between interface screens.
And despite the sizable knob, which you can see in the pictures, the Car Thing manages to maintain a relatively sleek profile without protruding excessively from the dashboard.
Personally, I would prefer if the company allowed the option to customize the knob's function so that I could control the smartphone's volume, as I can navigate using the touchscreen as well.
Perhaps this will be possible in a future version update.
The device comes in a small and minimalist cardboard box, which includes, among other things, a USB Type-C cable and various adapters for its installation.
Many of you probably remember how we used to unplug our radio devices and hide them in a drawer after getting out of the car.
Without a doubt, the Car Thing brings back that feeling with its construction.
All the adapters connected to the device body through a very strong magnet, preventing it from falling even during off-road drives.
In addition, along its top edge, you can find small buttons that can be easily configured to control different playlists or podcasts.
By pressing and holding one of the buttons during playback or by requesting through the voice assistant, I set up several playlists that I listen to frequently, as well as my morning radio show that I tune into during my commutes.
In this way, the feature made me feel that the Car Thing is more like a car radio rather than an extension of my smartphone.
From an Old Car to a Smart Car
After a fairly straightforward physical installation, I connected the Car Thing to the power source.
I was pleasantly surprised by the setup process.
The instructions were clear, connecting to the Spotify app took less than 5 minutes, and a few moments later, I arrived at the home screen.
In fact, the device connects to the smartphone via Bluetooth and controls the app like a remote control, allowing it to copy all the account information from it.
Meaning, you'll still need to connect your smartphone to the car, whether via Bluetooth or through an AUX cable, in order to listen to the music.
The home screen is familiar to all users of the app, as it places emphasis on album artwork and playlists, just like the smartphone application.
Additionally, on the home screen, much like in the app, you can find music recommendations based on your taste, the search screen, and your personal library.
As mentioned, you can navigate between different screens using the touchscreen or manually through the physical knob.
Furthermore, at any given moment, you can summon the device's voice assistant by saying 'Hi Spotify'.
Through it, you can play songs, playlists, albums, and even search for podcasts.
From my experience, she easily recognized my voice even when music was playing in the background and the air conditioning was blowing directly on the device.
This is most likely due to the four microphones installed on its top part.
It's important to note that currently, the voice assistant does not support Hebrew, and as of the publication of the article, there's no information about when such an update will be available.
So, is it worth waiting for?
My experience with the device has been great, and it's a positive surprise for me, considering that it's still in the initial release phase.
Even with intensive use during long trips, the device continued to function smoothly without disconnecting from my smartphone.
However, occasionally there was a minor glitch in the interface, but I believe Spotify will address such bugs with future version updates.
It's evident that the Swedish company has put a lot of effort into it in recent years, and among the various leaked versions on the internet during this period, the final product design is probably the one I like the most.
Still, when I saw the Car Thing for the first time, I wondered who exactly the company is targeting with it.
After all, its activity is mainly limited to controlling the app on the smartphone, and not much beyond that.
What's different from buying a cheap car mount and attaching it so that the smartphone is closer to us while driving?
The question becomes more relevant when considering that iPhones and Android devices are much more powerful than Spotify's device, and most of the time will provide the users with much more functionality.
But despite the above, as I used the Car Thing more and more, I realized how it can enhance the driving experience.
Absolutely, the ability to have Waze displayed on my smartphone screen and control the music on a separate screen has become something I've come to appreciate in the past couple of weeks.
One question remains - will Spotify even release the device to the general public?
And if so, will it also be launched here in our small country?
The Swedish company is not revealing much at the moment.
The company has not shared much information about the number of testers using the device worldwide or their specific plans for the limited launch in the United States.
The only thing we know for certain is the expected price, which is $79 (approximately 255 shekels).
For now, the Car Thing provides an initial glimpse into the concept that Spotify has been trying to crack for years.
Spotify Israel has stated that there is currently no information available about plans for launching the device in the country.
