Did you recruit talent for the company?
That's how you'll prevent competitors from "snatching" him/her from you.
The job market is still primarily controlled by the workers, and this is true twice as much when it comes to the most sought-after employees - the talents.
Here are a few tips that will help you retain talent in the workplace:
.
Despite the recent increase, the unemployment rate in Israel continues to remain one of the lowest in the world. Among the top ten countries in the OECD, the unemployment rate stands at 3.5% ( equivalent to 150,600 unemployed individuals, according to the Central Bureau of Statistics).
Meaning, the job market is still primarily controlled by the workers, and this is true twice as much when it comes to the most sought-after employees - the talents.
Regarding those professionals and managers who are hubs of knowledge, experience, and proven ability - labor market trends show that competition for them, the so-called "talents" as labeled by employers, still exists to its full extent.
The implication for employers is that in the current labor market situation, they can not afford to rest on their laurels even a moment after recruiting a sought-after talent. Once such a talent enters the company's doors, another company will already be trying to poach them away.
Exactly, the competition for talent is so intense that even after recruiting, many individuals will continue to receive tempting job offers. In fact, around 30% of employees leave within the first month of receiving a job and starting work.
Indeed, that's why savvy employers will transition from the talent acquisition phase to the talent retention phase quite seamlessly. It all begins with proper planning and creativity even during the onboarding process.
An efficient, well-structured onboarding process will cause the talent to becomes excited about their new role from day one and can even envision a future with the company.
Here are a few tips on how to prepare for and manage an effective onboarding process that will help preserve the new talent:
It's not a secret - organization's sharing and readiness.
Engage the stakeholders who will work with him on his recruitment, explain to them why he is crucial and important to the company and the role, and describe how you envision his contribution.
A new employee who arrives at a place where he is expected and his value is understood will feel welcome and will aspire to meet the expectations placed upon him.
Knowledge is power - aligning expectations.
Already on the first day, arrange a conversation to align expectations with the talent.
Get to know his professional background and explore where he envisions himself in the future, so you can present to him the diverse and unique tools that you and the workplace can offer him in order to reach that point.
We are all people - personal acquaintance.
During the onboarding days, try to get to know the talent beyond their professional attributes and take an interest in their hobbies and areas of interest.
A new employee who feels that they are interested in him at his place of work and is allowed to express themselves beyond the boundaries of their role will appreciate this and will want to maintain it.
Curiosity promotes advancement.
Already during the onboarding stage, you can create attractiveness that will make the talent eager to integrate quickly.
Do this not necessarily through discussions about bonuses and perks, but by exposing the talent to an exciting field or interesting technology, as such stimuli for creativity lead to curiosity and a growing interest in the workplace.
Furthermore, encourage the talent to voice their thoughts and opinions on various projects within the company, and make it clear to them that these contributions are valuable to the organization.
The writer is the CEO of Manpower Israel – the largest staffing and human resources company in Israel.
Electricity and Economy: The cost of not closing the coal-fired power stations in June - one billion shekels.
Report from the Research and Information Center of the Knesset: The failure to close the coal-fired power stations by the scheduled date in June 2022 is estimated at around one billion shekels.
• Electricity Company: "The policy regarding fuel usage is primarily formulated by the Ministry of Energy.
.
The economic cost due to the failure to close the coal-fired power stations by the scheduled date in June 2022 is estimated at around one billion shekels for the year 2022, as revealed by a report from the Research and Information Center of the Knesset.
According to the report, this cost is reflected in the electricity tariff for the consumer, which is expected to rise in the coming months due to the increase in coal prices.
In addition, in 2023, an additional surplus of about 900,000 tons of coal usage is expected. This will result in further costs for the electricity sector due to the failure to close the coal-fired power stations, assuming that the natural gas price remains significantly lower than the coal price.
The report states that the implication of reducing one billion shekels from the electricity tariff in 2022 resulted in a decrease of approximately 4% in the electricity consumption tariff for household consumers.
In other words, the economic cost of not closing the power stations is about one billion shekels, and the potential reduction that could have been for household consumers is around 4%.
It should be noted that as part of the reform in the electricity sector, it was decided, among other things, to establish a subsidiary company of the electricity company. This subsidiary will establish natural gas-operated units intended to replace the coal-fired units 1-4 at the Orot Rabin site.
Following this decision, a government resolution was adopted in July 2018, stipulating the cessation of operation of the coal-fired generation units 1-4 at the Orot Rabin power station.
The decision included timelines, so that the establishment of the first natural gas unit was set to begin in January 2020 and its operation was scheduled to commence in June 2022. Accordingly, the coal-fired generation units 1-4 will also cease operating at this time.
In response, the Electricity Company stated: 'The policy regarding fuel usage is primarily formulated by the Ministry of Energy.
In accordance with the ministry's decisions, Israel has been implementing a policy of minimizing coal usage for several years, even when the coal price is lower than the gas price.
Paying the price. Everything you need to know before the interest rate increase.
Decrees without bounds Next week, the interest rate on the shekel is expected to rise by half a percent.
By how much will the mortgage payment increase?
And what is recommended to do?
All the answers.
The intensifying inflation in Israel, which has already reached a rate of over 4% in the past year, will compel the Bank of Israel to raise the interest rate on the shekel as early as next week.
Analysts' estimates suggest an increase rate ranging from 0.25% to 0.5%.
If indeed the interest rate increases by half a percent, it will stand at 1.25%, the highest level in nine years.
This comes after years during which the interest rate in the economy was close to zero.
The sharp increase in the interest rate significantly raises the mortgage repayments by hundreds of shekels and places a heavy burden on household budgets.
With the help of Shai Tzror, a mortgage expert, we examined how much more we will pay and what is recommended to do right now.
If the interest rate increases by half a percent, how much will the monthly mortgage payment increase?
In a mortgage of 1.2 million shekels, consisting of 40% prime interest track, the monthly repayment will increase by 125 shekels.
How much did the average mortgage increase since the beginning of the year?
Since the beginning of the year, there has been a significantly sharper increase.
This is because the interest rates in most of the tracks that make up the mortgage (not just the prime track) have also risen – in the linked-to-index track and in the fixed-interest track.
If the interest rate does indeed increase by half a percent, the total increase, according to Tzror's estimate, will amount to approximately 620 shekels in a mortgage of around 1.2 million shekels.
The prime track (40% in this track) will experience an increase of around 280 shekels, assuming there is an additional 0.5% increase next month.
The variable interest linked-to-index track (26.7% in this track) will experience an increase of around 120 shekels.
The fixed-interest track - non-linked (33.3% in this track) will increase by around 220 shekels.
So what is recommended to do today?
For those who have a mortgage mostly linked to an index, Tzror recommends considering switching to non-linked tracks.
For mortgage holders whose monthly payments have significantly increased and find it difficult to manage the repayments, he recommends considering refinancing the mortgage and extending it over a longer period.
This is in order to reduce the payments despite the increase in interest rates, as it's always better to maintain repayments and avoid defaulting.
Regarding new mortgage takers, he strongly recommends getting to know the different tracks and tailoring the mortgage to their financial capabilities.
This way, in the future when interest rates decrease, they will be able to refinance their mortgage with minimal early repayment fees.
For buyers of homes from contractors, Tzror recommends prepaying installments to the contractor and taking out a mortgage now.
It's worth considering that the 'Construction Cost Index' significantly raises the property price even after the purchase contract has been signed.
The Construction Cost Index for residential properties has increased by 6.6% in the past year.
Against the backdrop of the increase in this index, yesterday the banking supervision announced that it is considering imposing a requirement to include the linkage within mortgages. However, the final decision on the matter has not yet been made.
The price of fuel is rising, and Israelis will have to pay over 8 shekels per liter in July.
The Ministry of Energy announced that the new price per liter of 95-octane gasoline will be 8.08 shekels.
Simultaneously, the reduction of 50 agorot per liter in the tax on diesel will be extended until the end of 2022.
Decade record. The price of gasoline will jump by 36 agorot per liter - and starting from July 1st, it will be over 8 shekels per liter.
The new price per liter of 95-octane gasoline will be 8.08 shekels, and those who wish to enjoy full service will need to pay an additional 21 agorot per liter.
Simultaneously, the reduction of 50 agorot per liter in the diesel tax will be extended until the end of 2022, as stated by the Tax Authority.
As mentioned, the price increase is due to the continued rise in oil prices, driven by the conflict between Russia and Ukraine and the increase in the value of the dollar.
Without the half-shekel discount subsidized by the government since April, the price of fuel would have exceeded an all-time high of 8.25 shekels per liter.
The discount's validity ends at the end of July, and the Tax Authority and the Treasury are currently promoting a public notice about an order extending the reduction in gasoline tax, which is half a shekel per liter, until August 9th.
Additionally, starting from August 10th, an additional reduction of half a shekel will be implemented, so only from that point on, the price of a liter of gasoline will decrease by one shekel, until November 15th, 2022.
As stated by the Tax Authority.
“We have reached a point where I can't remember five consecutive months of surplus in the government's income.
We started a few months ago with the topic of reducing the tax on gasoline.
We've been working for a week on extending the additional four months the excise, gasoline, and diesel tax - instead of half a shekel per shekel.
It's good for the industry and for the citizens.
If we lower it, it will impact inflation, reduce production costs, and alleviate the cost of living.
As the Finance Minister, despite the election system, I intend to focus primarily on this," said Minister Lieberman at the Herzliya Conference on Economy and Society of the Israel Democracy Institute.
As of today, over half of the fuel price consists of government taxes (excise tax and VAT) - and this is a high taxation rate compared to most developed countries.
The fuel price has a significant impact on the cost of living in the economy, as it affects household expenses and business expenditures, public transportation and flight prices, transportation costs, and more.
For the third time in a row: Ashdod - the most business-friendly city
Petah Tikva has reached second place in the Ministry of Economy's business performance ranking.
After them: Rehovot, Ashkelon, and Rishon LeZion.
Minister Barbibai: "The pandemic highlighted the importance of local governance in business development."
.
Ashdod is the most business-friendly city for small and medium-sized businesses.
This is for the third consecutive year - according to the Local Authorities Business Environment Index conducted by the Small and Medium Business Agency in the Ministry of Economy and Industry - that local authorities have been ranked.
In second place is the city of Petah Tikva, and in third place is Rehovot.
After them are located, in order: Ashkelon, Rishon LeZion, Tel Aviv-Yafo, Haifa, Ramat Gan, Holon, Be'er Sheva, Jerusalem, Bat Yam, Netanya, and Bnei Brak.
The agency compiles the index of local authorities.
This is the fifth time and its purpose is to serve as a tool for the local authority, as it allows each authority to compare its performance to other authorities in various parameters, as well as to analyze its performance in areas where it operates.
The index is based on several parameters that are examined in each local authority, which assess the level of "business-friendliness" of the authority to businesses within its jurisdiction.
The index divides the local authorities into three size categories based on the number of residents, as a local authority with up to 50,000 residents is not comparable to a local authority with more than 150,000 residents.
Tel Aviv-Jaffa jumped in the index this year.
The index is updated once a year and assigns four different ratings to each local authority: Satisfaction of businesses, accessibility to tenders, accessibility of information, and municipal taxes.
From the ranking, it can be inferred that Ramat Gan dropped from second place to eighth, Bat Yam dropped from fourth place to 12th, and Netanya dropped from fifth place to 13th.
A decrease in ranking does not necessarily indicate a decline in the local authority's services to businesses, and in many cases it might be due to the fact that other local authorities have improved their services to businesses more significantly and have therefore risen in the ranking, while the local authority that dropped in ranking might not have improved its services to businesses to the same extent.
Among the risers in the ranking, we can find Petah Tikva, which climbed from the sixth place to the second, and Rehovot which moved up from the twelfth place to the third.
Tel Aviv, which dropped from the fourth place to the eleventh in 2019, improved in 2021 and climbed to the sixth place.
"Businesses - The Engine of Growth"
The ranking indicates that Nof Hagalil leads among local authorities with populations ranging between 50,000 to 150,000 residents.
Following that, the ranking places Kiryat Motzkin, Mateh Binyamin, Modi'in-Maccabim-Re'ut, Kfar Saba, Ra'anana, Nahariya, Carmiel, Afula, and Hod HaSharon.
In the 28th and last place, Tiberias is located.
"The index is intended to encourage local authorities to ease the burden on small and medium businesses, starting from the opening of the business and throughout its activity with the authorities," says Minister of Economy and Industry, Orna Barbibai.
"Businesses constitute a significant growth engine for the Israeli economy, responsible for about 50% of the economic output and around 60% of the workforce in the economy,
The development of small businesses is a public interest for all of us, but local authorities have a direct impact on the businesses within their jurisdiction.
The COVID-19 pandemic highlighted the importance of local governance, and we have seen that authorities that actively promoted and encouraged the development of small businesses and found creative solutions for them became the first point of contact for them.”
Ran Kiviti, Director of the Small and Medium Business Authority at the Ministry of Economy and Industry, adds: "Local authorities play a central and essential role in the ability of businesses in their areas to thrive and prosper.
In the past two years, during which we have been dealing with the COVID-19 crisis, local authorities have had an even greater role in assisting businesses to survive in their respective fields and to survive in general."
2021 in the mail: 20 packages per household - and a jump in their weight.
46.6 million packages arrived in Israel during 2021 - similar to 2020.
The average weight per package is 435 grams - a 36% increase compared to 2020.
The busiest month: December, when the average package weight stood at 524 grams.
In 2021, 46.6 million mail packages arrived in Israel, nearly 20 packages on average per household - this is according to Israel Post data obtained by Israel Hayom.
The quantity of packages that arrived in 2021 is similar to that of 2020, where 46.5 million packages arrived in Israel, and is lower than in 2019, when 61.6 million packages were received.
However, this year there has been an increase of over 36% in the weight of the packages arriving from abroad.
In 2021, 20,253 tons of products arrived in Israel from abroad, marking a 36% increase compared to 14,860 tons in 2020 and 16,743 tons in 2019.
Changes in consumption habits
The average weight per package jumped by 60% over the two years, from 272 grams in 2019 to 435 grams in 2021.
The increase in the weight of packages is mainly influenced by two central trends, both from the seller's side and the buyer's side: Large overseas shopping websites are consolidating items for a single shipment and no longer send each product from the "shopping cart" separately in separate packaging.
From the perspective of the Israeli consumer, the quick delivery of shipments within just a few days from the moment of ordering supports the purchase of more daily-use products like clothing and gifts, of which consumers prefer to receive shortly after making the purchase.
In 2021, just like in 2020 and 2019, the month with the highest volume of incoming international packages and the highest number of items is December, with a total of 4.2 million packages arrived, weighing a combined 2,200 tons.
In the month of December, the average weight per package stood at 524 grams, which is 20% higher than the annual average weight.
The "Black Friday Effect"
More packages arrived in December than in any other month, likely due to the shopping holidays in November, such as Singles' Day in China, Black Friday, and Cyber Monday.
Large orders start arriving in Israel between one to two weeks after the purchase.
Research: Most employees in the economy are not aware that they can receive tax refunds.
Many employees are entitled to receive money from the government, which could amount to tens of thousands of shekels.
Did you change your workplace?
Did you go on unpaid vacation?
Did you move from the city to a rural settlement?
You may be entitled to receive a significant amount through a simple process.
All the details - inside
Most employees are not aware of the fact that they are entitled to tax refunds, which can accumulate to significant amounts.
The State Comptroller noted in a report two months ago that two million employees are entitled to tax refunds totaling 3.6 billion shekels, which means that it's also worth checking if you are eligible to receive tax refunds.
Many employees can receive a substantial amount, as four out of five renters are eligible for tax refunds.
In practice, however, only tens of thousands of employees actually file for tax refunds each year.
If you think that these funds would naturally go unnoticed, think again: Employees can submit a request to the Income Tax Authority for refunds for up to six years back.
The company Tax:On conducted an in-depth study among 4,000 of its customers regarding tax refunds during the year 2020.
The company has over 30,000 customers, so this sample reflects their distribution in terms of population groups and in terms of gender, ages, and geography:
The data indicates that during the course of 2020, due to the outbreak of the COVID-19 crisis and the layoff of hundreds of thousands of employees, significant changes occurred, with a central focus on a 15% increase in the average annual refund amount for the household, which stood at a sum of 4,300 shekels.
The reason is that unpaid vacation days compensation is lower than regular salaries, creating a gap between what the employee paid as taxes and what they actually need.
By the way, the highest refund received by a customer of the company in 2020 amounted to 121,054 shekels for returns over the past six years.
What can I get tax refunds for?
One of the reasons for receiving tax refunds is a change in the workplace.
81% of people who changed workplaces during the year generated a tax refund in an average amount of 2,943 shekels.
Another reason is maternity leave.
From the data, it can be inferred that 74% of women who gave birth and took maternity leave for more than 16 weeks were entitled to a tax refund with an average amount of 3,538 shekels for that year.
Another reason for the refund is donations.
100% of people who donate and pay taxes received a refund.
Another factor for the refund is failure to register credit points for expenses. 63%
of divorced individuals did not update their alimony credit points, resulting in a tax refund of 2,616 shekels for each year in which such credit points were not updated.
Due to unemployment - deduction for unpaid vacation: 93% of individuals who went on unpaid leave or were not unemployed and earned over 12,000 shekels received a tax refund of 4,021 shekels for the same year.
Additional reasons for tax refunds include: Refund for life insurance payments, mortgage life insurance, refund for a qualifying settlement, refund for losses in securities, failure to register credit points for a male related to childbirth and distribution of tax refunds based on geographic location.
- 94% of individuals who deposited into personal life insurance or took out a mortgage were eligible for a tax refund.
In an analysis conducted, on every one million shekels of mortgage over 25 years, the accumulated tax refund for the period amounts to over 20,000 shekels for the overall mortgage period.
100% of those who moved to a qualifying settlement received a tax refund for the transition year, because approval for residency in a qualifying settlement is granted only after 12 months from the day the resident's status is changed to a resident of that settlement, and in a result, in practice, the first year is subject to full tax payment.
79% of customers who hold securities were eligible for tax refunds in the mentioned years.
However, individuals who hold securities should still check every year, as losses are not automatically carried over from year to year; they need to be reported through the submission of a report.
56% of men who have a newborn child do not register credit points for the birth year in their salary deduction.
The refund amount can reach tens of thousands of shekels over the course of six years.
This phenomenon is mainly present in the Arab sector.
Tax:on CEO, Tal Karmon: 'The COVID-19 crisis has led to a much more active engagement of the salaried public in Israel.
It is interested, checks, and demands what he is entitled to in income tax refunds.
It becomes clear that staying at home, being on unpaid leave, or after being laid off, for many hundreds of thousands of Israelis for several months, has prompted many renters to thoroughly examine what they are entitled to from the government.
It's important to know that nowadays, all the procedures for obtaining tax refunds can be done digitally, easily and simply, without the bureaucracy that deterred many in the past."
The Job Market: Fewer candidates for a position, higher salary.
AllJobs report for 2021 summary: At the forefront of demand - positions without experience •
The volume of offered positions increased by 50% •
Seeking employment, but not storming the market.
In the just-concluded year, there has been a 15% decrease in the number of submitted resumes, and for each position, an average of only 23 candidates competed, compared to 41 candidates in the previous year - according to a report by the AllJobs website summarizing the year 2021, on the COVID-19 crisis and its impacts on the job market in Israel.
According to the report, job seekers were primarily interested in saturated job sectors such as administration and sales, to which a total of 1,738,485 resumes were sent.
Nevertheless, entry-level positions led the demand with over 38,000 searches - likely due to a resurgence of inexperienced young individuals seeking immediate employment after completing their unpaid leave payments..
The number of searches for sales and administration positions was 35,000 and 32,000 (respectively), for drivers and couriers there were 11,000 searches, and for security positions there were slightly less than 9,000 searches.
On the other hand, despite the COVID-19 crisis, the salary in 2021 increased by 2% compared to 2020, and the average salary in Israel stood at 11,675 shekels gross.
The monthly salary in the software field averaged 17,915 shekels, and in information systems analysis, it stood at 17,140 shekels.
However, there was a salary gap of over 2,000 shekels between the center and the periphery: In the central part of the country, it was 12,500 shekels on average, compared to 10,795 in the north and 10,135 shekels in the south.
In terms of gender, the average wage gap between women and men, which can also be explained by job type and working hours, remained at 36%.
Men earned 13,295 shekels, compared to women's salary of 9,740 shekels.
Trying to return to normalcy.
On the business side, there was a broad growth recorded in almost all sectors of the economy, and businesses were eager to have more and more employees..
As a result, the job supply increased by 50% and reached a record high of over 40,000 positions on AllJobs.
A survey conducted by the website among employers found that 50% were optimistic about their economic status in 2022, with 30% indicating their intention to increase their hiring, but 72% acknowledged that they would face challenges in doing so this year.
The largest supply was for positions without experience - there were over 58,000 such positions on the website.
Following those were customer service and administration roles, each with around 44,000 positions, sales and software with 41,000 positions each, education and teaching with 24,000 vacancies, and warehouse roles still in demand with 19,000 vacant positions.
Einav Boimfeld, Director of Research and Content at AllJobs, said: 'Job seekers are trying to return to normalcy but are not storming the market, mainly due to the lack of attractive positions in their eyes.
As well, the prolonged disconnection from the job market makes it difficult for them to return, and some have found creative ways to make a living”.
