"Not taken for granted:" ‘Sabliminal’ is observing the Sabbath - and preparing for independence day.
Celebrating the fact that 'we can live as we just want to,' excited for the upcoming meeting with the audience, and making sure to spend time with the children.
The weekend and Independence Day of Kobi Shimoni, ‘Subliminal’.
What does a typical Friday look like for you?
“The weekends are the most significant moments in life, for me.
The Kiddush and tradition are deeply rooted in my soul.
My Fridays are dedicated to the children, Or (10) and Yonatan (8).
I pick them up from school, we buy flowers and supplies for the Kiddush, have lunch together, and do something fun as a family, like playing soccer, riding horses, or playing with remote control cars.
Sometimes we go to the beach, or just wash the car, but we always stop by the way to buy a gift at the neighborhood toy store - and there's always another excuse.
When we return home with all the gifts, the aromas of cooking welcome us”.
How does your Friday meal look?
"I am blessed the candles around me.
On my side, there's a Persian-Tunisian kitchen, full of salads and an atmosphere of laughter, music, singing, and joy.
On my wife's Iness side, who is also a wonderful cook, Ukrainian dishes come in, which are rich and spicy, with lots of meat.
When we arrive at my mother-in-law's, even from the building lobby, amazing aromas waft out from her apartment.
Usually, I do the Kiddush, together with the kids, who know it by heart.
In the end, my fun after the meal is to lie down on the rug, and the kids jump on me as if I'm some kind of inflatable toy.
Do you have a special childhood memory from Friday evenings?
As a child, I would wake up on Saturdays to the sounds of Israeli music on Reshet Gimmel radio and the skits of Hagashash Ha-hiver, which we all knew about."
My dad loved nature, and we traveled a lot around Israel, mostly to the north.
Every corner in the country held a special place in his heart.
He passed away three months ago after a severe illness, and for him, the Kiddush and Shabbat was the holiest of holies, especially in terms of bringing the whole family together.
Recently, I released a song in his memory called 'Watching Over You,' which I created together with Osher Cohen.
I believe he would have been proud of this creation that sanctifies the bond between a father and a son”.
Soon we will celebrate the 74th Independence Day. As an enthusiastic Zionist, what are your feelings about the holiday?
"Independence Day is a sacred day for me, and it's part of the meaning and identity I hold.
In Persia and Tunisia, my parents were forced to hide their Jewish identity, whereas I am an Israeli Jew who is fortunate to live with my children in our own country.
Two weeks before Independence Day, I would already be climbing trees and attaching strings with Israeli flags to my house.
These days, my Independence Day is filled with performances, and I always meet an ecstatic crowd celebrating the fact that we can live the way we want.
We need to ensure that our children, grandchildren, and future generations will also have this opportunity, and to remember that nothing here is taken for granted.
Her Friday: Esti Zackheim is blessing the Sabbath.
"My dream is to set up a big table and invite all my dear departed loved ones”: Esti Zackheim dreams of a Friday night meal and how she copes with the fact that her husband observes the Sabbath?
Tell us about your preparations for the Sabbath.
.
The preparations start already on Thursday night when I return from a show or workshop and cook until three in the morning everything that requires a long cooking process, like goulash, roasts, and sauces.
On Friday, in the first part of the day, I dedicate time to myself, meet with friends for coffee, attend a show or a movie, or participate in rehearsals.
During the summer, the Sabbaths come in later, and I have plenty of time to relax in the neighborhood garden and watch the sunset or simply enjoy a good TV series.
For the Sabbath meal, I usually host my mom, Varda, who is celebrating her 89th birthday, and also friends”.
Can I share more about the cooking?
"I love shortcuts.
For example, instead of peeling and chopping 10 onions and shedding tears, I buy a bag of frozen chopped onions and fry them.
On my Shabbat table, you can find meat dishes, vegan tofu dishes, oven-baked potatoes, and roasted cauliflower.
I prepare most of the dishes, and they of course get warmed up on the hot plate on Shabbat.
Alejandro, my partner, prepares chicken soup, vegetable salad, and in the winter - the Cholent”.
Your husband is religious and you come from a secular background.
How does it work?
Living with someone who observes the Sabbath is an endless compromise.
'Love your neighbor as yourself’ in practice.
He can't join family trips, so I often find myself packing the kids and joining friends' family outings.
In addition, I'm also the designated driver for the kids, the one who picks them up on Friday nights from parties and gatherings.
On the other hand, I also enjoy the benefits of his Shabbat observance, because usually I don't appear on Shabbat and get a kind of 'forced vacation' - and that's a good thing.
Who would you like to host on Shabbat?
"I would set a large table and invite 'my departed loved ones'.
Sometimes I imagine what it would be like if my late brother Daniel z”l were still alive, or if my father Shneior z”l could see my children: Uriel (23) and the twins Tamara and Naama (16 and a half).
"We probably would have had lively discussions about soccer and politics, and enjoy each other”.
Do you have a special childhood memory from Friday evenings?
“We were a warm and united family.
On Friday afternoons, my mom would prepare a stack of schnitzels, bring hummus and pita bread from the market, and roast eggplants for tahini salad.
Afterwards, we would go to Aunt Hannah in Yad Eliyahu, or as she used to say, 'Yad Alayke’, and she would prepare blintzes.
Since I was the only one who didn't like raisins, she would prepare several portions for me without raisins.
She saw me, the youngest among the siblings, and took care of me.
On Saturdays, we used to take a tour with my father at the Jaffa Port, and he would show us where he and his twin brother, Grisha, arrived in the country with nothing”.
