"Double standard: In Russia you cancel a show but in Israel you didn't cancel?”
Nick Cave responds to criticism
The singer addressed the criticism directed at him by a Turkish fan, who accused him of double standards
The singer responded: "The invasion of Ukraine is very different from the Israeli-Palestinian conflict
"
Nick Cave canceled a performance in Russia earlier this week due to the war and announced that he "stands by Ukraine and prays that the madness will end soon."
In doing so, the esteemed Australian singer joined artists and bands like Iggy Pop, Green Day, and Franz Ferdinand, who also canceled their performances in the invading country.
But in the case of Cave, his cancellation announcement received a slightly different context.
A Turkish fan named Ahmet accused the singer of being hypocritical, as in 2017 Cave refused to cancel two concerts that took place in Israel, despite receiving significant criticism from pro-Palestinian organizations.
During his visit to the country, Cave told the local media, "In the end, I am here for two reasons: The first reason is because I love Israel and the Israelis, and the second reason is that I am against anyone who tries to censor and silence musicians."
The same Ahmet praised Cave's statements in favor of music and against politicization.
The fan even published on the uncensored personal site of the singer, "The Red Hand Files," a post in which he argued that Israel is also an occupying state, and therefore the situation in Palestine is similar to that in Ukraine.
"What bothers me about your message regarding Ukraine," wrote Ahmet, "is that you didn't show the same support for the Palestinians, who are also suffering under a brutal regime.
In fact, you portrayed Israel as a functioning democracy, but in my opinion, Israel is primarily responsible for the suffering of the Palestinians.
I'm very saddened by this because you represent a double standard here," the Turkish fan concluded.
But the story doesn't end here, as Cave chose to respond to Ahmet in a long and detailed letter, in which he emphasized that "Russia's invasion of Ukraine is very different from the ongoing conflict between Israel and the Palestinians.
The first scenario is an unprovoked attack by one state on its neighbor, in the hope of altering the overall security order of Europe.
The second scenario is a complex clash between two nations.
The conflicts are indeed similar in that innocent people who share a tragic fate are forced to seek refuge in shelters.
I feel great sympathy for all these communities - no matter where they are located or who they are”.
Cave added that although he doesn't want to elaborate on his views regarding the Israeli-Palestinian conflict, he certainly supports the Palestinians as well, mentioning that over the past 20 years, he has actively participated in events aimed at contributing to their well-being.
"But it's not a time for debates, Ahmet," the singer clarified, "it's a time to come together and support the Ukrainians, who are currently facing a catastrophe on their land.
I have wonderful fans in Russia, and I know that many Russians strongly oppose Putin's regime's actions.
If I could perform for them, I would do it," he stated.
In light of the decrease in infection rates: The COVID-19 projector will resume managing the Ziv Medical Center.
Professor Salman Zarka was appointed to the position in July 2021 and led the COVID-19 treatment policy during the third and fourth waves.
At the request of the Minister of Health, Nitzan Horowitz, he will continue concurrently in his role as the Projector.
Professor Zarka: "I'm glad that the Omicron wave continues to recede, but we still have an obligation to be prepared for another wave."
.
Against the backdrop of the decrease in COVID-19 cases, Professor Salman Zarka, the Coronavirus projector, will return to lead the Ziv Medical Center in Safed on Sunday.
At the request of the Minister of Health, Nitzan Horowitz, he will continue concurrently in his role as the Projector.
"I am glad for the sake of the citizens of Israel that the Omicron wave continues to recede and that we are returning to our normal way of life," said Professor Zarka, adding, "Nevertheless, it is still our duty to be prepared for another wave of illness as a result of the virus still being present here in Israel and around the world."
Professor Zarka was appointed to the position in July 2021 and led the COVID-19 treatment policy during the third and fourth waves.
Starting from May 1st, Israel returned to a state of "between waves," which involves reducing most of the COVID-19 arrays while maintaining the capability to perform sequence tests and investigations that will serve as a foundation for action in case a new variant is detected.
Occult infection
In a report from the National Knowledge and Information Center for the Coronavirus Response, published this morning, it was noted that "there is a decrease in the average number of new confirmed cases to below two thousand per day, on a weekly average basis, alongside a decrease in the number of hospitalized and severely hospitalized patients."
However, it was emphasized that "there is a significant occult morbidity, and in practice, the number of infected individuals is much higher.
The number of institutional tests conducted in the community (excluding returning travelers, m.y.) is low and stands at less than 20,000 tests on average per week.
The low volume of tests makes it difficult to identify the trends of the illness and understand the situation”.
State Comptroller's Report: The actual budget for most of the years of activity of the Basket of Medicines Committee was lower than the recommended budget.
According to the report by Matanyahu Angleman, for over 20 years of the committee's activity, the Ministry of Health did not closely monitor the committee's activities.
The report also states that the minutes of the committee meetings are published with significant delays, if at all.
Furthermore, the State Comptroller recommends increasing transparency in the activities of the subcommittee and updating the working procedures of the basket committee.
Another deficiency found is that since the committee began its activity, the Ministry of Health did not request the healthcare providers to report on the extent of drug usage and utilization from the basket, which would have allowed for analysis and control of the budget allocated to them.
The Basket of Medicines Committee is one of the most influential public committees that impact our daily lives and our health.
Every year, the committee decides on new medications to be provided to the public free of charge through the healthcare providers - however, a new report by the State Comptroller, published today (Tuesday), warns that the committee has been operating for over 20 years without conducting control reports on its activities, and without the Ministry of Health and the Health Council supervising and examining its activities.
"Yisrael Hayom" journalist, Ran Raznik, adds that the investigation by the State Comptroller was carried out following the ongoing exposés in "Yisrael Hayom" regarding the failures of the Basket of Medicines Committee.
According to the report by Matanyahu Angleman, he recommends "making corrections and improvements in the process of expanding the basket, which will lead to a higher quality utilization of the health services budget that the public is entitled to."
Throughout the existence of the mechanism for adding drugs to the medication basket, between the years 1998 and 2021, medications worth a total of eight billion shekels were added to the state budget, while the addition varied annually, ranging between 0 to 500 million shekels.
In the years 2019, 2020, and 2021, requests were submitted to add approximately 800 new drugs and medical technologies to the healthcare services basket, with a total annual cost of over two billion shekels.
In practice, the budget allocated for the expansion of the healthcare services basket was smaller than the scope of the requests.
During most of the committee's operation (90% of the time), the budget increase was less than 1.5% of the health basket, a percentage recommended by various committees as the desired increase.
The Comptroller notes that there is a need to examine and regulate the annual increase amount in order to enable certainty and long-term planning.
Furthermore, Angleman pointed out that “The transparency model in the work of the basket committee is lacking”.
For example, the procedure of the Basket Committee states that the minutes of the meetings, which are closed to the public, will be published within 60 days. However, in practice, the minutes are published with a delay of 160 to 109 days, and sometimes the final meeting minutes are not published at all.
"The delay in publishing the minutes harms the transparency of the decisions; as a result, the ability of proposers – health organizations and pharmaceutical companies – to submit revised requests promptly and relevantly, after receiving feedback from the previous round may be compromised, so they could analyze the reasons for their proposals' rejection, improve and adjust their suggestions, and reevaluate their feasibility for acceptance in the next round," noted the State Comptroller in the report.
"The Ministry of Health should publish the minutes according to the specified timelines in the procedure".
Out of thousands of submissions, only one financial note was submitted
Additional criticism from Angleman relates to the preliminary process of evaluating the technologies submitted to the drug basket.
The auditor found that nearly half (46%) of the technologies submitted did not pass this stage, but the Ministry of Health does not publish the reasons for the rejections.
Another flaw concerns the activities of the subcommittee of the drug basket, which is closed to the media and the public, and where patient numbers and drug costs are discussed.
The Comptroller recommends including a public representative or considering the option of publicly disclosing the discussions without revealing confidential commercial details.
According to the procedure under which the Health Services Basket Committee operates, it is stipulated that an "economic assessment" should be submitted for a request to add a drug to the basket.
However, in practice, over the years, only one economic assessment was submitted out of thousands of applications – and the committee makes its decisions without an economic assessment.
For example, during the discussions of the Basket Committee for the years 2021-2019, requests to add anti-obesity drugs to the basket were submitted.
The report indicated that requests were not accompanied by economic assessments, including estimates of potential savings from reducing obesity-related diseases or avoiding Gastric bypass surgeries.
Furthermore, the report highlights that decisions of the Drug Basket Committee are not always aligned with the goals and strategy of the Ministry of Health.
For instance, in 2019, the Ministry of Health defined preventive medicine and preparedness for treating chronic disease growth as goals. However, in the context of decisions regarding the expansion of the Drug Basket, there was not enough emphasis on achieving these goals.
The Comptroller also raises a concern that since 2011, services have been included in the Drug Basket that are not the responsibility of the healthcare providers, including rehabilitation and mobility devices and various vaccines, provided by the Ministry of Health ("The Third Addition").
This is done when the legal framework for this step is organized only retrospectively.
In the past six years, a total of 74 million shekels from the supplementary drug basket have been used for these services.
Angleman recommends that the Ministry of Health update the working procedures of the drug basket committee and determine whether a separate financial allocation is needed for these services.
About a third of the new medications added to the drug basket are categorized as "cost-neutral drugs," meaning their usage does not result in additional expenses to the healthcare providers as they replace existing treatments.
The Comptroller suggests considering an option where these medications would follow a separate and expedited path, allowing for updates to the drug basket multiple times a year rather than just once.
There is no oversight over the use of especially expensive medications.
The criticism also highlights that since the establishment of the basket Committee, nearly 20 years ago, the Ministry of Health has not requested the healthcare providers to report and did not oversee the extent of the usage and utilization of medications in the basket, information which could have enabled the Ministry to analyze and control the budget allocated to the healthcare providers.
Over the years, only two reports have been published that refer to the years 2006-2009, and even these were published with a significant delay (the latest was published this year and dealt with the budget utilization in the years 2007-2009).
"The delay in conducting tests could lead to difficulties in data collection and analysis, irrelevance of conclusions drawn from the testing after such a long period, suboptimal pricing of the subcommittee, and making decisions based on non-final findings," the report states.
Additionally, the ministry does not oversee and supervise the usage of particularly expensive medications and has not generated insights.
These are 10 medications that accounted for 62% of the addition to the basket (1.7 billion shekels from 2016 to 2021).
In response to this, the auditor wrote: "It is recommended that the Ministry of Health conduct private audits on these medications and technologies and analyze the extent of their usage compared to estimates.
Conducting audits and analyses would allow for systematic conclusions regarding the work process of the Basket Committee and the Subcommittee, as well as the method of preparing estimates during the pricing of medications and technologies, in order to improve them”.
"Appalling and incomprehensible": Heated debate in the Health Committee about the poisoning at the Dafna House.
The measurements of the first vaccinated individual who passed away were normal ten minutes before her death.
Committee Chairman, KM Silman: 'If people cared that the kitchen would be like at home, it wouldn't look like this.'"
Ten minutes before the first dependent individual, aged 40, from the 'Dafna House' residence in Holon, passed away from food poisoning, medical measurements were taken that were normal," claimed the residence's manager during today's (Tuesday) discussion in the Health Committee.
"We have overnight caregivers who check during the night, and there's a nurse making rounds.
There were several reports of diarrhea, and the same resident, in fact, the last time measurements were taken from her was 10 minutes before she stopped responding, and they were normal.
She was under observation like the rest of the residents with diarrhea.
She is under nursing care, we went to bring a lift to assist with her transfer, and then the same resident did not respond.
We began resuscitation and called the clinic nurse," described the residence manager of what happened on Sunday morning at the residence.
It is an incident in which three residents passed away, six were hospitalized, and a total of a quarter of the residence's residents (33 out of 131) suffered from gastrointestinal symptoms due to consuming contaminated goulash meat.
The residence manager made these statements against the backdrop of allegations that death from food poisoning indicates neglect and lack of supervision on the part of the caregivers.
Dr. Naama Nuss, the head of epidemiology at the Tel Aviv Health Office, stated that 'we cannot definitively determine what caused the deaths of the three residents.
Only blood tests were taken from them."
Furthermore, it was raised in the discussion that even from the residents who were hospitalized, it was no longer possible to obtain a stool sample as they did not have diarrhea, thus it is not possible to definitively determine the cause of death and illness.
Furthermore, the engineer representing the Ministry of Health indicated that “The Ministry of Health examines the state of hygiene in kitchens at institutions once every four years, upon request from the Ministry of Welfare or upon request for license renewal."
In the Ministry of Welfare, it was acknowledged that an investigation committee has not yet been appointed for this case and for the previous case of malnutrition among residents, which occurred three months ago at the 'Bnei Zion' institution in Sharon.
The chairman of the Health Committee, KM Idit Silman, said during the discussion: 'If people cared that the kitchen would be like at home, it wouldn't look like this.
The residents in welfare residences need more.
They are health-sensitive and require extra supervision and care.
It is appalling and incomprehensible what transpired there.
The shocking findings were revealed even after they were informed that the Ministry of Health was coming to investigate.
Where is the supervision and responsibility of the ministries?
How come in such a discussion, the ministers and the directors-general of the ministries aren't present to provide an explanation about what's happening here?”
Yigal Nachatomi, CEO of Beit Eckstein, who manages the residence and even ran the residence himself, said, 'Hundreds and thousands of people in the entire system rise with one goal in mind: To do good for people.
The individuals who passed away are people I personally cared for.
I personally lifted one of the residents onto my hands.
This is a deeply unsettling event for us."
Smadar Una, a former resident of an equivalent facility in Gilo, lashed out at him and said “Enough with the lies and pretty words.
I was there”.
Gali Barami, a representative of parents in EKIM Israel, said: “We complained in the past about the food and they didn't take the criticism".
Oren Helman, founder of the 'Equal Chance' initiative for integrating people with disabilities, criticized the fact that the names of the deceased residents were not published: “Their names are not known at all.
Are they worth less?
"They are disregarding the lives of our children".
Suspected negligence in Walfson: The surgeon caused a tear in the heart - and the patient died.
This is the first procedure performed by Dr. Faras Abu Akar as the head of the Thoracic Surgery Unit at the hospital.
The chairman of the doctors' committee complained that the director, Dr. Angel, was warned before his appointment.
The hospital: “He is respected and experienced”
First publication: A horrifying mistake occurred at the government hospital, Wolfson, in Holon, as during a surgery, the doctor accidentally caused a tear in the patient's heart, leading to his tragic death.
The surgery was performed on an 83-year-old lung cancer patient on April 19th.
This was the first surgery performed by Dr. Faras Abu Akar at the hospital after being appointed as the head of the Thoracic Surgery Unit at Wolfson.
During the surgery, intended to drain the area around the patient's heart, the surgeon accidentally caused a large tear in the heart, leading to severe bleeding and resulting in the patient's death.
However, the exceptional complication opened Pandora's box, raising challenging questions regarding the hospital's management.
The director of the Oncology Institute and chairman of the doctors' committee, Dr. Ronen Brenner, called for an investigation into the incident in a letter he sent to the hospital's director, Dr. Anat Angel.
In the letter, serious allegations were raised about the conduct of Dr. Angel and the appointment of Dr. Abu Akar, following the departure of the former unit head, Dr. Benny Zukerman, to Sheba Medical Center in Tel Hashomer.
A massive hole in the heart
According to Dr. Brenner's letter, the patient was sober, functional, and under his care for the past four years.
Recently, his illness worsened, and abnormal fluid accumulation was discovered within the heart sac, where the heart muscle is located.
Furthermore, the surgeon, Dr. Abu Akar, believed that he could perform the surgery.
According to the complaint, a serious complication occurred during the surgery, and Dr. Hagay Dekel, the director of the Cardiothoracic Surgery Department at Wolfson, who was performing surgery on a child in the adjacent room at the same time, was called urgently to the operating table and saw a massive hole in the heart”.
According to him, the heart was devoid of blood, the blood pressure was zero, and the surgical approach was incorrect.
In addition, Dr. Brenner also reported that Dr. Dekel approached him and said that Dr. Abu Akar is not suitable, professionally and personally, to manage the Thoracic Surgery Unit at Wolfson.
However, despite the explicit warnings and despite him being supposed to be the direct manager of the thoracic surgeon, Dr. Angel conducted a tender without involving him and appointed Dr. Abu Akar to the position.
He also noted: “This is not a complicated process, which takes a few minutes”, and added: “It is impossible to ignore the flawed process of appointing Dr. Abu Akar to the position.
The question arises whether there is direct responsibility of Angel for the surgical failure and the patient's death”.
Experienced surgeon
Before 'Israel Hayom,' information and allegations from other senior doctors were presented, reinforcing the questions raised in the incident by Dr. Ronen Brenner.
Dr. Mordechai Shimonov, director of Surgical Department A at Wolfson, responded to Brenner's complaint and wrote that Dr. Abu Akar is “one of the most experienced surgeons in the country, but he is relatively young in thoracic surgery”.
He also added that Abu Akar was selected through a proper tender process and Dr. Dekel did not participate in it, in line with his statements about his intention to 'disengage' from the thoracic unit.
He also noted, “I also wasn't involved in the process, and I might have been supposed to be.
Dr. Shimonov wrote that Dr. Faras Abu Akar began working on April 10th and is entitled to 100 days of grace. “All the hospital doctors were impressed by his professionalism and motivation, and his willingness to work.
He has already performed dozens of similar procedures, and unfortunately, the current case ended as it did in a regrettable manner.
Wolfson Hospital responded: “We share in the family's sorrow.
This is a patient of the oncologist Dr. Ronen Brenner.
The mentioned thoracic surgeon is an esteemed and experienced professional, selected through a tender process to manage the Thoracic Surgery Unit affiliated with the Surgical Department at Wolfson Hospital.
"According to Dr. Hagay Dekel, his statements that were quoted are not accurate and were taken out of context.
It should be noted that the patient was, unfortunately, in a very critical condition.
The hospital is transparently examining the details of the case, and the Ministry of Health is familiar with the case details".
