Healing Model: Three senior doctors talk about their mentors
Prof. Galia Rahav misses the insight and wisdom of Prof. Marvin Shapiro, may he rest in peace, especially during the days of the pandemic.
Dr. Shlomi Kodesh remembers, even beyond his role, the encouragement from Prof. Saul Suckenik, may he rest in peace.
Dr. Efrat Baron-Harlev thanks Dr. Tommy Scheinfeld for the lesson in empathy with the patients
Three key individuals in the hospitals write about those who inspired and encouraged them to be better caregivers and better human beings.
Three senior doctors, three life and profession mentors. On the occasion of Israeli Doctor's Day, "Israel Hayom" invited Prof. Galia Rahav, Dr. Shlomi Kodesh, and Dr. Efrat Baron-Harlev to reflect on the figures that accompanied them at the beginning of their journey and helped them become who they are today.
Prof. Galia Rahav, Director of the Infectious Diseases Unit at Sheba Medical Center.
About Prof. Marvin Shapiro, may he rest in peace
The encounter that opened my eyes and changed my life.
If I hadn't met Prof. Marvin Shapiro, may he rest in peace, who was the head of the Infectious Diseases Unit at Hadassah Medical Center, I would probably have remained a specialist physician in internal medicine.
He is the one who made me love the field of infectious diseases and influenced me to engage with it.
I met him at the Hadassah Medical Center corridors, around the 1980s of the previous century.
For a moment, I didn't think I would leave internal medicine, as I enjoyed patient care. However, Prof. Shapiro showed me that the field of infectious diseases manifested itself not only in neurology but also in internal medicine, and essentially in every domain.
I am grateful to him for introducing me to this field.
Throughout the journey, I admired his investigative approach that delved into the root of the problem.
The discussions with him were analytical and logical.
He was a doctor through and through, who loved his patients and taught me not to take things for granted and to thoroughly examine everything.
He was a genuine and honest person, devoid of ego, qualities that I greatly admired in him.
At first, when I was asked to choose a physician who would be a role model for me and influence me more than anyone else, I intended to choose my father, Dr. Yosef Rakover, may he rest in peace, a Holocaust survivor who served as a doctor in the partisan unit.
He was an incredible doctor who influenced me to pursue medicine - but he also reminds me of Marvin Shapiro.
Both of them, for example, coined phrases that doctors still use today - for instance, "tissue is the issue", meaning that taking a biopsy of the affected organ helps determine which medications to give; or "when you use it, you lose it," explaining that excessive antibiotic use leads to bacteria becoming resistant to them.
Prof. Marvin Shapiro, may he rest in peace, was married to a physiotherapist who worked at Hadassah and was the father of two daughters.
He passed away about a year ago, and when I visited his family during the seven-day mourning period at his home.
He was someone - a knowledgeable and wise epidemiologist who volunteered for everything.
He never complained, not even during his difficult illness.
He was one of the first doctors in the team to treat epidemics, and he is sorely missed during this period.
If he were with us today, I'm sure I would consult with him, and I'm confident that he would be one of the leaders of the team for treating epidemics.
Published by: Meital Yassur Beit-Or
Dr. Shlomi Kodesh, Director of Soroka Medical Center
About Prof. Shaul Suckenik, may he rest in peace
He was a teacher and a friend who supported me and nurtured generations of doctors.
.
I first met Prof. Shaul Sochnik, may he rest in peace, when I was a fourth-year medical student, and I arrived for a rotation in internal medicine in the 4th internal medicine department that he managed.
I continued to return to the department during my sixth year of medical school, and I conducted my final project under his guidance, writing a computer simulation on a patient with polyarthritis (inflammation in multiple joints).
Shaul had a significant impact on every significant junction in my professional life over the course of 20 years, and he was the most significant person in shaping my identity as a physician; not only professionally, but also - and mainly - on a personal and humane level.
During my internship, I debated between family medicine and internal medicine, and I consulted with him about choosing my specialization.
In the end, I chose to specialize in internal medicine under his guidance at Soroka Medical Center.
During my specialization, he provided me with constant guidance in various aspects, spanning scientific writing (I apologize, Shaul, I didn't dedicate enough effort), patient interactions, teamwork in a highly professional environment - an area where the department excelled - and essentially, in every aspect related to medicine.
To this day, I identify in myself, both as a physician and as a manager, qualities that stem from Shaul.
When I completed my specialization and debated whether to go abroad for further training, Shaul pushed and guided me. He assisted me with recommendation letters and advised me on how to proceed.
The period of further training was a very important time for my professional development, and without Shaul's support and encouragement, I'm not sure it would have happened.
Upon my return, when I received an offer to join the hospital's management team, once again Shaul was the one who supported and assisted me.
Later on, together we successfully navigated through challenging periods in the Internal Medicine division.
Shaul had a remarkable ability to seamlessly integrate the roles of teacher, manager, colleague, and team player, without allowing his various responsibilities to interfere with each other.
I aspire to succeed like him in this unique combination.
He nurtured generations of students, interns, and residents who are currently spread throughout the medical system in Israel, perpetuating his excellent work and legacy through their actions.
It is an honor for me to be associated with this group.
Published by: Ilya Yagurov
Dr. Efrat Baron-Harlev, Director of the Schneider Center for Pediatric Medicine
About Dr. Tommy Scheinfeld
The man who taught me medicine, and above all, attentive listening.
Dr. Tommy Scheinfeld, the founder and former director of the Pediatric Intensive Care Unit at Schneider Children's Medical Center, taught me to be a pediatric intensivist, but more than that, he taught me to think.
The obvious lesson I learned from him is to care for the most complex and critically ill children.
The children, some of whom were healthy just moments ago, are now teetering between life and death.
Naturally, it involves conducting extremely difficult conversations, perhaps the most challenging ones, with families who never imagined they would find themselves in such complex situations in the Intensive Care Unit with their children.
It might sound strange, but it has become self-evident.
But I learned even more significant and profound things from him.
Looking back, as a physician who is also a manager and a manager who is also a physician, I can clearly see the connection between these worlds today; the education I received from Dr. Scheinfeld bridges the gap between them.
Dr. Scheinfeld taught me to listen carefully to many things: To listen to the children, to listen to the monitor, to listen to the nursing staff, to both the young and the experienced care teams, and to listen to the parents.
All of this needs to be done not only to communicate more effectively and successfully, but also to gather all the available information that can prevent further deterioration.
Preventive processes in the treatment of children exist everywhere, and of course in critical care.
Attentive listening and engaging in conversations promote a deeper understanding, both from the perspective of the caregiving team and from the side of the patients and their families.
My understanding today as a manager is that these insights are also true when looking at the entire system.
The more thorough and meticulous the deep understanding that incorporates all involved parties in the dialogue, the decision-making process becomes more precise, tailored to the situation, and primarily early enough to prevent future, immediate, or distant harm.
This is why Dr. Tommy Scheinfeld is much more than just an inspirational figure for me.
He is a person who taught me a lot about medicine, but mainly taught me to think quickly and accurately, to listen, and then to implement.
Published by: Yaron Doron
