Medical negligence during different stages of childbirth
In order to be eligible for compensation, the plaintiffs must prove, in addition to negligence, that the harm was caused due to that same negligence.
Birth is one of the most joyous and exciting events in a family's life.
However, unfortunately, sometimes childbirth experiences can end with serious harm caused to the mother or the newborn as a result of medical staff negligence.
In cases where childbirth concludes with physical harm to the newborn or the mother, it is necessary to examine the sequence of events that led to the harm and consider seeking legal advice.
A lawyer specializing in medical negligence will examine whether there were failures in the conduct of the medical team during the various stages of childbirth that led to harm. If necessary, they will seek consultation from a relevant medical expert in the field.
It is important to emphasize that not every error in medical treatment by the medical team constitutes medical negligence (in the legal sense of the term), and various complications during childbirth do not necessarily indicate that the management was negligent.
So when is it considered negligence?
When a doctor's mistake arises from a lack of skill or falls below the reasonable standard of care, and this lack of skill and deviation from the accepted standard of care result in harm to the patient that wouldn't have occurred if the doctor had acted differently.
In this article, we will examine the different stages of childbirth, explaining the complexities that can arise in each stage, and when they might constitute medical negligence.
The contractions stage
The contractions stage lasts on average between 8 to 14 hours.
During this stage, the cervix gradually opens (to allow the baby to pass during delivery) and by the end of the process, it is expected to reach a diameter of about ten centimeters.
The majority of cases of medical negligence during the contractions stage focus on failure to identify fetal distress prior to delivery, which can result in harm to the newborn, sometimes even leading to cerebral palsy.
Cerebral Palsy (CP):
Cerebral Palsy may result from failure to identify or delayed recognition of the umbilical cord entanglement, which manifests as a deficiency in supplying oxygen to the fetal brain tissue during the second stage of labor.
In general, closely monitoring the condition of the laboring mother and accurately interpreting the monitor that tracks the fetal heart activity should lead to early detection of fetal distress, enabling the medical team to quickly intervene and deliver the baby before irreversible harm occurs.
Cases in which the medical team ignores signs indicating that the fetus is experiencing oxygen deficiency or misinterprets the data available to them, especially from fetal monitors, or responds with delay to distress evident in the monitor - may constitute negligence.
Brain damage can also be caused as a result of a umbilical cord prolapse and also as a result of an undetected uterine rupture.
Even in such difficult events, it is appropriate to investigate whether the medical team acted properly.
For example, attorney Anna Reif Lignza from the law firm "Kaspi Sror & Co." specializes in representing victims of medical negligence, explains that her firm handled a case of a child who was injured during his birth when the midwife ruptured the amniotic sac while the baby's head was too high. This led to umbilical cord prolapse (where the umbilical cord precedes the baby's head during birth), resulting in compromised oxygen supply to the baby's brain (due to pressure on the cord), and as a result, the child was born with severe neurological damage.
In another case, the attorney shared that her firm filed a lawsuit due to severe medical negligence against the team in the maternity department of a major hospital, when during childbirth, the medical team failed to timely recognize clear signs that should have raised strong suspicion that the mother was suffering from a rupture of the uterus in the area of the previous cesarean section scar.
The fetus that was expelled through a tear in its mother's uterus into the abdominal cavity may experience severe fetal distress until its delivery at a later stage, when it is on the brink of death.
Due to the severe fetal distress during the course of his birth, the child suffered complex neurological disability.
It should be emphasized that in order to be eligible for compensation, the plaintiffs must prove, in addition to the negligence, that there is a causal relationship between the medical staff's negligence that led to the failure to identify the fetal distress and the harm caused to the newborn, so that the harm was caused due to the negligence as mentioned, and not due to any other reason or cause.
The examination of the causal relationship will be conducted by assessing medical measurements that, according to medical literature, only when they are met, a causal link exists between the failure to identify the fetal distress and the occurrence of brain injury.
Among other factors, measurements of fetal blood acidity levels, Apgar scores, the presence of neurological and systemic damage, and more are examined.
Fetal demise
The Active Labor Stage
The active stage of labor begins when the cervix dilation reaches a diameter of 10 centimeters and concludes with the birth of the baby.
Unfortunately, most medical complications occur during this critical stage.
Delay in childbirth and avoiding the performance of a cesarean section.
In certain cases, dysfunctional labor, meaning lack of progress in the active labor process.
In such situations, a cesarean section is commonly performed to prevent various potential harms that may arise for the fetus due to the delay in childbirth.
"There are cases where failure to perform a timely cesarean section could result in irreversible harm to the fetus," explained attorney Reif-Lignza.
"For example, we handled a medical negligence lawsuit involving the wrongful death of a newborn due to significant delay in performing a cesarean section," she added.
Contrary to established medical practice, the medical team failed to identify the fetal distress and perform a cesarean section despite the particularly slow progress of the labor.
"The delay in performing the procedure resulted in extensive systemic damage to the newborn, ultimately leading to her death shortly after birth".
Negligence in childbirth with vacuum extraction.
In situations where there is a significant and immediate danger posed to the mother or fetus, necessitating an expedited conclusion of the birth, sometimes a vacuum-assisted delivery (vacuum extraction) is performed.
In this process, a vacuum 'cap' is attached to the baby's head using suction and pulled outward with force.
Consequently, this procedure entails risks and could potentially cause harm to both the fetus and the mother. Therefore, it requires caution, precision, and a high level of skill.
In such cases, medical negligence might manifest when the doctor fails to adhere to necessary guidelines and performs the procedure despite contraindications, e.g. where the fetus's head is positioned too high in the pelvis, performing the procedure for an extended period beyond what's permissible, or when the doctor continues attempting the procedure beyond the allowed number of attempts despite repeated failures.
In such cases, if the vacuum extraction procedure resulted in harm to the newborn – among other things, it could potentially cause skull damage and bleeding that may lead to the development of brain injury – there may be grounds for filing a lawsuit for damages.
Erb's Palsy
Erb's palsy refers to nerve damage occurring in the brachial plexus (a network of nerves that connect the spinal cord to the upper shoulder), and when this injury occurs during childbirth, it's important to investigate whether the damage was a result of medical negligence by the delivering team.
The injury presents itself as weakness in the muscles of the arm and can even lead to complete paralysis of the entire arm.
This paralysis sometimes occurs due to difficulties in delivering the baby, often associated with a condition called "shoulder dystocia." - an emergency situation during childbirth where the baby's shoulders become lodged behind the mother's pelvic bone after the head has already emerged.
When should you suspect that the paralysis was caused as a result of medical negligence?
In cases where the estimated weight of the fetus indicates that it is macrosomic, meaning that it is expected to be born with a weight exceeding 4.5 kilograms, it is preferable to deliver the mother through a cesarean section according to the guidelines.
When the baby's weight exceeds 4 kilograms, it's important to consider a cesarean section due to risk factors such as gestational diabetes and prolonged second stage of labor.
In cases where the medical team disregards the abnormal estimated weight of the fetus or other additional risk factors and chooses to proceed with vaginal delivery despite the risk of shoulder dystocia and Erb's palsy, there is a reasonable possibility that medical negligence is involved.
Indeed, in case 2694/90 in Israel, the Supreme Court ruled that "the risk of shoulder dystocia during childbirth can be predicted in advance with a certain degree of accuracy, and the way to prevent its occurrence when there is a concern about it is by performing a cesarean section".
The placental delivery stage
The separation of the placenta from the uterus and its expulsion occurs due to uterine contractions after the birth, and it is accompanied by bleeding.
In most cases, the process continues for up to half an hour after the baby's delivery, and according to many instances, it occurs spontaneously without medical intervention.
After the placenta is expelled, the medical team will examine whether it came out intact or if any fragments remain in the uterus.
During this stage, complications can occur that may lead to severe harm for the mother.
One of the well-known complications arising from retained placental fragments in the uterus is called "Asherman's syndrome" meaning the adhesion of the uterine walls due to inflammation caused by the presence of placental fragments, such condition can negatively affect the uterine lining, making it difficult for pregnancy to establish.
Therefore, in cases where the medical team did not identify retained placental fragments or did not take all necessary measures to prevent harm to the uterine lining despite suspicion of placental remnants, medical negligence might be involved. Such a case should be thoroughly investigated by an experienced attorney in the field.
Maternal mortality
Maternal death during childbirth is a relatively rare occurrence.
In such cases, the event that was supposed to bring happiness and joy to the entire family turns, unfortunately, into the most tragic event for her.
In certain cases, the medical team may not detect timely bleeding in the mother or may respond with delay to the bleeding as mentioned.
"For example," attorney Reif-Lignza shared with us, "our firm filed a lawsuit concerning a maternal death case, where in the same incident, the medical team ignored and did not respond for many hours to the vital concerning signs of the mother, they also delayed diagnosing a massive and uncontrollable hemorrhage, which occurred as a known complication of the underlying condition she was suffering from".
"In another case", attorney Reif-Lignza conveyed, "our firm represented a close relative of a mother who passed away following the birth of twins due to hemorrhage originating from the cesarean section incision that wasn't sutured properly.
In the same case, the mother complained of severe pain and weakness after the surgery, yet the medical team did not adequately address her complaints and clinical condition, they only responded with a delay after her body systems began to fail, ultimately leading to her passing.
Uterine loss
In severe cases, medical negligence during childbirth can lead to uterine rupture. Attorney Reif Lignza states: "Our firm handled a lawsuit against a hospital where the basis of the case was a uterine removal due to medical negligence following childbirth.
In the same case, the young 31-year-old mother lost her uterus due to inadequate treatment of significant postpartum hemorrhage, which was observed by the medical team after childbirth. Despite this, timely actions that could have prevented the harm were not taken”.
What are the compensation amounts awarded in medical negligence lawsuits related to childbirth?
Compensation for birth-related injuries due to medical negligence includes various components of damages, with the most significant amounts often awarded for pain and suffering, medical expenses, rehabilitation and treatment costs, loss of income, and disability benefits for the victim and potentially even for their parents, and as well additional components of damages may also be considered.
Compensation awarded to an injured child for loss of income and disability benefits is often calculated based on the average income in the economy in most cases.
Additionally, compensation also includes medical expenses, costs of medical equipment and rehabilitation, adapting housing for the child's needs, mobility aids, and more.
"The amount of compensation is determined in each case according to its circumstances," attorney Reif-Lignza explains, and she adds, "Today, most medical negligence claims are settled through a mediation process that reduces the likelihood and risk for both parties in managing the proceeding", but she also mentioned that there are cases that only conclude with a court verdict. In such instances, if the lawsuit is not rejected, the plaintiffs can receive full compensation for all their damages, for example, in a case our firm handled, a district court ruling awarded over ten million shekels in compensation to a child who suffered brain damage due to delayed recognition of fetal distress”.
In summary
Medical negligence during childbirth is undoubtedly the nightmare scenario for every family.
In such cases, a proper legal examination of the sequence of events that led to the tragic outcome, carried out by a skilled attorney experienced in handling medical negligence claims, can help you secure the compensation you rightfully deserve.
This is the reason for the prevalence of the eye condition keratoconus in the south
Research has shown that there is a connection between the development of the disease and close relatives' marriages
The highest prevalence was found in the Bedouin sector
Expert: "It's possible that in any community where there are frequent marriages between cousins, a high prevalence of the disease can be found".
Keratoconus is an inherited eye disease that causes several visual impairments.
It is very important to diagnose it early and find appropriate solutions to prevent the worsening of the condition.
In recent years, several studies have been conducted to help understand the development of the disease, and innovative treatments have been developed.
The new research provides a scientific basis for suspecting that keratoconus is a genetic disease.
A recent study that focused on the transformation of the corneal shape from convex to concave, revealed that the underlying cause of the disease and the weakening of the cornea's structure, leading to its distortion, is linked to an enzymatic imbalance, leading to a situation that the free radicals might potentially damage the proteins within the cornea, causing changes in its structure.
The source of that enzymatic deficiency is genetic, a fact that strengthens the hypothesis that keratoconus is an inherited disease.
According to Prof. Ariela Gordon-Shaag, Head of the Optometry Sciences Department at Hadassah Academic College, "In a study published among Arab students in Haifa, a prevalence of 3.2% of keratoconus was found.
The highest prevalence was among Bedouin students, with 20% having keratoconus, although the sample size was relatively small”.
The researcher added that this is not a surprising finding: "There is a high prevalence of keratoconus in the Bedouin sector.
In our studies, we found that close marriages are a risk factor for keratoconus.
This way, in any community where there are frequent marriages between cousins, a high prevalence of the disease can be found".
In this context, it should be noted that this finding is significant in light of the strongly implied conclusion: In cases where there is a family history of keratoconus, all family members are advised to undergo appropriate eye examinations promptly.
According to Arza Fruchter, Clinical Optometrist B.Sc., "We receive about ten times more referrals to the clinic from remote peripheral areas, mainly from the southern regions, compared to the central area".
Fruchter adds that "in the last decade, I've noticed that the majority of patients come from the periphery, especially from the Be'er Sheva area.
This is mainly due to the high prevalence of consanguineous marriages within families (especially in the Bedouin sector), various allergies, and a lack of awareness for proper treatment of the issue”.
So, how is the disease diagnosed?
Fruchter explains that keratoconus typically develops during adolescence or late teenage years (around ages 15-16 or 20).
The disease involves a decrease in vision, accompanied by an increase in astigmatism.
Patients with keratoconus report distorted and/or blurred vision of shapes and objects.
These symptoms worsen as the disease progresses, which usually develops slowly and gradually over the years.
However, the disease can also develop rapidly and reach its peak within just a few months.
Many patients also report increased sensitivity to light.
