A senior police officer: "Government policy and goal setting are required here".
Israel's police may have launched an operation to mitigate the phenomenon of illegal residents, but there is still a long way to go.
There is currently no single entity in the State of Israel that comprehensively addresses this issue".
"If we want to deal with the phenomenon of illegal residents, a government policy is required, and from it, goals, missions, and responsibilities must be derived.
Currently, no single entity in the State of Israel comprehensively addresses this issue", says a senior police officer.
Until a month and a half ago, before the escalation in the security situation, the phenomenon manifested itself with about 20,000 to 30,000 infiltrators entering daily through breaches in the fence.
In addition to that, between 100,000 to 110,000 Palestinians with work permits enter Israel daily through 34 controlled crossings.
It should be noted that Palestinians have been employed in Israel since the end of the Six-Day War, and the number of permits in each sector is limited by the quota set by the Israeli government according to the security, economic, and political situation in the State of Israel.
Permits are issued by the IDF through the Coordination and Liaison Administration.
In light of this, an illegal resident is not necessarily a palestinian whose entry is forbidden due to criminal involvement or links to attacks; in many cases, it refers to Palestinians whose entry is prohibited because they do not comply with the permitted quota.
It is emphasized that those who carried out the attacks in Ariel, Dizengoff, and Elad were considered illegal residents, but they were not supervised because they had not committed any criminal offenses that required security forces to monitor their movements.
"Therefore, there is no significance to their entry through breaches in the fence", says a senior security official, "Anyone who wants to carry out an attack can enter the country through controlled crossings, and there have been cases like this in the past".
Thousands of Arrests
Following the attack in Elad and in light of the increasing alerts for attacks, the police launched a wide-ranging operation to locate illegal residents.
As of the end of the weekend, approximately 16,000 illegal residents were arrested.
Out of those, about 600 were investigated, criminal cases were opened against them, and around 200 were detained.
According to the police's prosecution policy, proceedings against illegal residents are only conducted against recurrent offenders or those involved in criminal activities again and again (Recidivists).
An illegal resident who is arrested for the first time is investigated, documented, and then returned to the territories.
Sometimes this process repeats itself on the second occurrence, but it is only on the third occasion that they are arrested, detained, and charged with unlawful presence.
According to the law, if an illegal resident is apprehended within a range of about 50 to 100 meters from either side of the separation barrier, the military legal authorities handle their case.
Data obtained by "Israel Hayom" indicates that in 2021, the police dealt with 40,010 illegal residents, smugglers, and infiltrators.
7,405 illegal residents were arrested, and criminal cases were opened for 19,533 of them.
The number of employers, smugglers, and infiltrators handled by the police in 2021 was 6,537.
469 were arrested, and criminal cases were opened for 5,640.
"The fundamentals of the phenomenon of illegal residents do not depend on the police, the IDF, the Israeli society, or the Palestinian society.
They depend on other factors", says a senior law enforcement official.
"To address this phenomenon, we must address their motivation to work in Israel, and on the Israeli side, we must impose a price that prevents them from crossing the barrier.
Stakeholders in this issue claim that the failure to impose this price is due, among other things, to a lack of detention facilities and the fact that arrests only occur when accompanied by other offenses or when dealing with recidivists.
Legal experts argue that the decision to impose a price on illegal residents only began after the third arrest, partly because the courts cannot cope with the number of daily arrests.
Anyone who examines the punishment will find that it is not deterrent enough".
There is great complexity
"Illegal residents", says a police source, "are complex individuals".
He can be a father for a family that enters the country to work and earn a few shekels and then return.
This is the basic platform, and many types of illegal residents enter the country to commit criminal offenses or terrorist attacks.
An illegal resident can be an adult or a minor.
In the past, the police have arrested illegal residents as young as 16, and even children aged 8 to 10 who were sent by their parents to intersections on the roads to earn a few shekels from drivers.
"This also complicates the matter because in such cases, we need to bring the parents and file charges against them for child abandonment," says a senior police officer.
Most Palestinians are employed in Israel as day laborers.
The most non-common jobs are in construction and advanced building jobs.
In the past, local authorities also employed illegal residents in garbage collection, mainly in the north.
Out of 34 crossings, there are about 18 main crossings.
Some crossings are for vehicles and goods, some only for people, and some serve both purposes.
All crossings are supervised by the IDF and the Crossing Authority.
Illegal residents are usually smuggled into Israel by private individuals because it involves easy cash.
"There are those who do this to make a living, and there are gangs whose main business is smuggling illegal residents", says a senior police officer, "Usually, most of them are Arab Israelis who speak the same language and communicate with them.
This can cost between 100 to 300 shekels per person.
Registered companies don't engage in this because if the company is caught, it may be shut down".
In the police, they emphasize that under certain conditions, transporting illegal residents can be considered as an offense.
"A taxi driver who works with licenses and insurance, who collects Palestinians at designated points at set hours, including organized pickup, is usually not breaking the law", says a senior police officer, "Those who know they are smuggling illegal residents usually pick them up at night at hidden points, including disembarking at hidden points.
Most of these guys prefer to travel in an old car because they know it might be seized".
