A Glimpse into the "Asaf" Facility
Getting Ready for the Next Attack: A series of terror attacks carried out in the spring by Palestinians and Israeli Arabs, resulting in the deaths of 19 people and injuring around 70 civilians, led the Border Police to develop a unique technique for training fighters to engage terrorists within a civilian population and conduct shooting while in motion.
Exposed by "Israel Hayom": A Glimpse into the "Asaf" Facility
The grassroots terror focuses on targeting civilians, aiming to disrupt the necessary sense of security required for the normal functioning of a civilian population.
The wave of severe attacks this year, including incidents in Be'er Sheva, Hadera, Bnei Brak, Ariel, Elad, and notably the one that occurred in early April on Dizengoff Street in the heart of Tel Aviv, carried out by a terrorist infiltrating a crowd, prompted the police to engage in creative thinking for the development of a tool to train fighters to confront terrorists within a civilian population.
The thought process was led by the Training Division of the police force and the Border Police.
They competed in various police districts under the title 'Commanders Leading Learning,' where each district was required to develop tools to aid in the improvement of surveillance and combat skills of the fighters, officers, and commanders.
Within this competition and as a response to the need for Border Police fighters to practice shooting while in motion and in scenarios of this kind, Asaf Ben David, a counterterrorism instructor for the Jerusalem Border Police, developed the 'Asaf Facility.' This facility comprises a dynamic target connected to a telescopic pole, which is attached to a harness worn by the instructor.
Once the instructor has strapped the carrier to his waist, he can practice the fighter in front of him by controlling and moving the target to different sides and ranges.
It's worth noting that in recent years, Border Police officers and fighters have encountered numerous attacks in which the assailant posed a threat while in motion within crowded civilian areas.
The current version of the 'Asaf Facility' is based on components and parts derived from various fields.
For instance, the telescopic pole used in the facility was adapted from maintenance and cleaning equipment.
This facility allows the simulation of shooting while in motion within a civilian population, aimed at a dynamic target while maintaining visual contact with the subject, managing movement during shooting, selecting a path for advancement, and conducting selective shooting exercises, all while preventing harm to uninvolved individuals.
Warrant officer Asaf Ben David, for whom the facility is named, states, "The facility we developed is a breakthrough in training and preparing fighters and police officers.
