Research determines: Zoom meetings impact creativity.
Approximately 2,100 engineers and academics worldwide were asked to develop solutions to a problem – some in video meetings, some in face-to-face meetings.
The result: Virtual meetings impede creativity and thinking outside the box.
The research was led by Columbia University: "Visual focus on the screen hinders the ideation process."
Anyhow, it's not so bad: There is no impact on work performance or critical thinking.
A recent scientific study published in the journal Nature examined the influence of video conferencing on the creativity of participants, compared to in-person meetings.
Unfortunately, it was found that creativity is indeed affected in virtual meetings through screens.
The research question, led by Melanie Brooks, an assistant professor at Columbia University, was whether remote computer-based meetings preserve the creativity found in in-person brainstorming meetings or if creativity and free thinking decline due to the distance.
The research itself began in 2016 but gained significant momentum during the two years of the COVID-19 pandemic when many people shifted to remote work.
"In an in-person meeting, people are moving in the room, use objects, and rely on them for creative thinking", says Brooks.
"In a computer-based meeting, on the other hand, the focus on maintaining eye contact with others comes at the expense of creative activity in the brain.
Visual concentration on the screen narrows cognition.
People are more visually focused on the video during interaction, which hinders the broad and expansive ideation process".
The space is constrained.
To examine the experiment's results and verify if they would repeat themselves, the tests were conducted twice - once at Columbia University and once in real-life situations - with engineers who were already acquainted.
At the university, the researcher divided a group of 602 faculty members and students into two parts - in one, the participants were asked to meet in person and develop solutions to a problem, and in the other, they were asked to do it via a computer.
Simultaneously, 1,490 engineers from five countries in Europe, the Middle East, and South Asia were similarly divided and asked to solve a presented problem in a new way.
In both cases, a decrease in creativity and thinking outside the box was found among those who met virtually via video.
Jay Olson, a post-doctoral researcher at McGill University in Canada, who specializes in measuring creativity, was not surprised by the results.
In his view, during creative thinking activities, people often look at their surroundings for inspiration, which helps generate new ideas. However, in video meetings, thinking is concentrated on the screen and does not expand in a way that allows creativity to flourish.
"When people are in the same room, they look around and see the space, objects, and situations that can trigger new associations.
In contrast, the research shows that computer-mediated relationships change our focus so that we are more internally and screen-focused, and this narrows innovation and idea generation through observing the environment and thinking beyond".
There is no impact on critical thinking.
Nevertheless, before managers bring employees back to the office, the researchers point out that "working via a computer did not affect autonomy itself and not the critical thinking of individuals on innovative proposals when they had to choose the best idea from a set of ideas.
In other words, the impact is specific to creativity and not to other forms of computer-mediated work."
Professor Ellen Langer, a psychology professor at Harvard University, also supports these findings.
According to her, "There is a distinction between mere creativity, such as coming up with new uses for a paperclip (one of the research questions, AG), and the solutions of work.
"It's also possible that when employees become more familiar with each other or when they work from home, creativity may indeed improve."
Both Professor Langer and Dr. Olson also suggested future research in which such meetings are interrupted by thinking and wandering around the room to see how this activity will affect the final outcome.
Dr. Olson also proposed that, following this research, employees should not return to work solely based on one study but instead conduct further investigations in the field.
