Travelers returning from countries that are not red are exempt from isolation in quarantine facilities, the foreign tourists return.
Those landing in Israel received messages from the Ministry of Health stating that they are exempt from the obligation to isolate with a negative coronavirus test result.
Only after that, the Ministry issued an official notice stating that this exemption applies only to travelers coming from countries classified as "orange," even though there were reports of receiving the notice by those returning from "red" countries.
Additionally: Tourists from "orange" destinations will be allowed to enter the country, and many "red" destinations are expected to be removed from the list.
In the height of the pandemic - the end of isolation for returning from abroad?
The Ministry of Health sent messages to those returning to Israel this morning (Monday), stating that they are exempt from isolation upon receipt of a negative coronavirus test result performed after landing in Israel.
This includes those returning from "red" countries.
Some of the messages sent informed returning individuals that they can be released after receiving a negative test result or after 24 hours at the latest, and some received the exemption after receiving the negative result.
Only after that, an official notice was issued by the Ministry of Health, stating that starting from midnight on January 4, 2022, vaccinated or recovered individuals returning from "orange" countries will undergo a PCR test at Ben Gurion Airport and will enter isolation for 24 hours or until they receive a negative result (whichever is earlier).
The decision will be anchored in an order by the Director-General of the Ministry of Health and will be brought to the approval of the Knesset Health Committee.
The Ministry clarified that vaccinated or recovered individuals who have already returned to Israel from an "orange" country and received a negative PCR test result upon entry to Israel will end their isolation tonight at midnight and are not required to undergo a second test.
However, travelers from "red" countries have reported receiving the same message.
Those who are not vaccinated or recovered and return from an "orange" country will enter home isolation for 14 days, with the option to shorten the isolation period after receiving a negative PCR test result performed from the 7th day after landing in Israel (the day of arrival being the first day).
The decision to lift most of the restrictions on travelers, especially vaccinated individuals, comes one day before a hearing in the Supreme Court filed by the Association of Travel Agencies, Open Skies Headquarters, and the Hotel Association.
In the hearing scheduled for tomorrow, the petitioners are expected to demand the removal of all other "red" countries from the list, while Professor Itamar Grutto supports them with his opinion.
Foreigners will also be allowed to enter.
The Prime Minister and the Ministers of Foreign Affairs, Health, Interior, Tourism, and Transportation have agreed that starting from Sunday, January 9, 2022, the entry of vaccinated/recovered foreigners (according to the Ministry of Health's definition) from "orange" countries will be allowed, subject to online form submission in advance, performing a PCR or antigen test before boarding the plane, performing a PCR test upon arrival in Israel, and then entering isolation for 24 hours or until receiving a negative test result (whichever is earlier).
Non-vaccinated/non-recovered foreigners (according to the Ministry of Health's definition) will not be allowed to enter Israel.
Foreigners from "red" countries, except those approved by the Exceptions Committee, will not be allowed to enter Israel.
The group quarantine outline will not be renew at this stage.
What about "red" countries?
The Health Ministry's committee for classifying countries has recommended to the government to remove the following countries from the red list and move them to the orange list: South Africa, Hungary, Nigeria, Spain, Portugal, France, Canada.
The countries that remain on the red list at this stage are: UAE, USA, Ethiopia, United Kingdom, Tanzania, Mexico, Switzerland and Turkey.
Another option being examined by the Health Ministry is to exempt vaccinated individuals returning from red countries from isolation.
At the moment, it is unclear if there is a connection between the messages received by those returning to Israel this morning and the guidelines that may be issued by the Health Ministry on this matter.
The Health Ministry has not yet responded.
The skies are starting to open up: The Health Ministry is changing the restrictions on entry to the country.
Vaccinated individuals returning from orange countries will be required to isolate for 24 hours.
The countries United States, Turkey, the United Kingdom, and the United Arab Emirates will be classified as red.
After several weeks during which it was very difficult to find a destination to travel to without restrictions, and after all returning from abroad were required to quarantine, alongside a ban on tourists entering Israel, changes to the regulations were decided upon yesterday, significantly easing restrictions at Ben Gurion Airport.
The Ministry of Health decided to recommend canceling the three-day quarantine requirement for Israelis returning from orange countries.
Until now, anyone vaccinated or recovered according to the Ministry of Health's definitions who returned from an orange country was required to quarantine for three days, subject to two coronavirus tests.
Now, the quarantine that vaccinated and recovered individuals returning from orange countries will have to enter is a maximum of 24 hours, or until they receive the results of the coronavirus tests performed after landing at Ben Gurion Airport (the earliest among them).
Those not defined as vaccinated or recovered will still be required to enter a seven-day quarantine, subject to two coronavirus tests, or 14 days without the second test, even if they return from an orange country or a red country.
Vaccinated or recovered individuals returning from a red country will also be required to enter full isolation.
The current updated list of red countries recommended by the Ministry of Health, which still needs government approval, includes the United States, Turkey, Tanzania, Ethiopia, Mexico, the United Kingdom, Switzerland, and the United Arab Emirates.
In all of these countries except Turkey, the percentage of positive cases entering the country in the past two weeks is more than 5% of the total entries, which automatically places them on the red countries list.
The rate of increase in the number of patients from Turkey is fast, with over 4% of those returning from there testing positive, which is why it was decided to include it in the list of red countries.
The prominent countries removed from the red list are: France, Spain, Portugal, and Canada.
Meanwhile, starting from January 9, fully vaccinated tourists according to the Ministry of Health's requirements will be allowed to enter Israel without the need for quarantine, under conditions similar to those for Israelis returning from an orange country.
Also in this case, the decision is subject to government approval, which will be discussed in the coming days.
It's important to note that there are few cases in which the government does not approve the Ministry of Health's recommendations in this regard.
Tourists against the restrictions.
The Association of Travel Agencies, the Open Skies Headquarters, and the Hotels Association filed an appeal to the Supreme Court to lift the restrictions on flights.
The country removed most of the restrictions yesterday but, as mentioned, left eight significant countries on the list of red countries.
In the discussion to be held this morning in Jerusalem, the appellants are expected to demand that the country cancel the list of red countries.
Supporting the appellants' position is Professor Itamar Grutto, who is expected to be present at the hearing.
Minister of Tourism Yoel Razvozov, who has supported easing restrictions on foreign tourists entering Israel in recent weeks, said yesterday: "The cancellation of quarantine for vaccinated individuals returning from abroad and the return of tourism for the vaccinated are the right and correct things to do at this time.
I thank my government colleagues who understood the dire situation of the tourism industry and agreed with me that the damage outweighs the benefit.
The vaccine is the best response to the pandemic, and as such, it is up to the vaccinated public to live a life as normal as possible alongside the coronavirus".
